	<h3 id="firstthing">Monday (assembly, history, <span class="caps">ICT</span>)</h3>


	<p>• <strong>Meet Mr Darwin:</strong> For an engaging kick-start to the week, hold a special assembly to introduce the children to Darwin and his work. Perhaps a teacher could dress up as Darwin himself and provide an autobiographical account (who he was, where and when he lived, how he came to develop his ideas, his main theories and how they were received). Other brave teachers could act out a sketch to demonstrate Darwin’s ideas (the origin of species through natural selection). A Victorian-style post box could be set up in the foyer and, throughout the week, children could write letters or questions for Darwin that the teacher in role as Darwin could address in an assembly on Friday.</p>


	<p>• <strong>Darwin’s time (history):</strong> To appreciate Darwin’s impact, it’s important to gain an understanding of the society in which he lived. Ask the children to research Victorian society, clothing, work, entertainment, religious values, family life, technology, and so on. (<a href="http://magazines.scholastic.co.uk/search/search?&#38;now=mag_id&#38;search[mag_id]=21881&#38;search[query]=the+victorians">Take a look at resources on the Victorians from the <em>Junior Ed <span class="caps">PLUS</span></em> archive.</a>)</p>


	<p>• <strong>Darwin’s life (ICT):</strong> Give children the opportunity of further exploring Darwin’s life and work. The <a href="http://www.nhm.ac.uk">Natural History Museum website</a> is an excellent information source. Likewise, the ‘Down House’ page on the <a href="http://www.english-heritage.org.uk">English Heritage website</a> contains an interactive element in which the viewer can look around Darwin’s study. The children could also complete <a href="http://magazines.scholastic.co.uk/resources/49575"><strong>Photocopiable,</strong></a> ‘Darwin trivia challenge’. Their answer sheets could be put into a school post box and a winner drawn out at the end of the week.</p>


	<p><strong>Quiz answers: 1) <em>On the Origin of Species</em>; 2) Emma Wedgwood; 3) <em><span class="caps">HMS</span> Beagle</em>; 4) Mockingbirds; 5) 73; 6) Alfred Russel Wallace; 7) Westminster Abbey; 8) Worms; 9) Down House; 10) Abraham Lincoln</strong></p>


