	<h3 id="secondthing">Tuesday (cross curricular, science, history)</h3>


	<p>• <strong>Beagle journey (cross curricular):</strong> In 1831, Darwin sailed around the world on the <em><span class="caps">HMS</span> Beagle</em>. He used this time to observe and collect countless species of plants, animals and fossils, an act that eventually led him to develop his theories. You could transform the school hall or playground into a giant world map, depicting the different places Darwin stopped on his journey. The locations included: Plymouth, Cape Verde Islands, Salvador (Brazil), Punta Alta (Argentina), Tierra del Fuego (Argentina), Falkland Islands, Rio Negro (Argentina), Chiloé Island (Chile), Galápagos Islands (Ecuador), Sydney (Australia), Cocos Islands (Keeling Islands), Mauritius (Indian Ocean), Cape Town (South Africa), Bahia (Brazil), Pernambuco (Brazil) and Falmouth (UK). Assign each class within the school (or group of children within a class) a different country. They should investigate what Darwin might have seen when he visited (the animals and their habitats). The children should collect photographs, draw pictures or make models to depict these. Their work can be set up in the appropriate area of the ‘map’ later on in the week. Then, with the teacher acting as a ‘tour guide’, the children could be led through the different stages of the voyage.</p>


	<p>• <strong>Observing animals (science):</strong> Ask the children to make observations of an animal. This could be an insect or bird in the school playground or you may wish to use an ant farm or worm box in the classroom – Darwin himself was fascinated by earthworms and dedicated years to studying them. The children could sketch the animals and make notes about their behaviour.</p>


	<p>• <strong>Animals and adaptation (science):</strong> Ask a volunteer from an animal/bird sanctuary or a local vet to visit the school to talk to the children about the way animals adapt to their environment.</p>


	<p>• <strong>Archaeological dig (history):</strong> Talk to the children about the way archaeologists find out about the past. Set up ‘digs’ using large containers of sand or loose dirt and bury items in them. Show the children how to carefully brush away layers until they find their artefact. Talk about the discovery of ‘Lucy’ – an Australopithecus afarensis skeleton, which was at the time (1974), the most complete and oldest hominid specimen. Look out for our creative topic next month celebrating British archaeology.</p>


