	<h3 id="fourththing">Thursday (literacy, drama, <span class="caps">PSHE</span>)</h3>


	<p>• <strong>The Origin of species (literacy/drama):</strong> Ask the children to research the impact that the publication of <em>On the Origin of Species</em> in 1859 had on society and religion at the time. What were the main ideas expressed in the book? Why did it cause controversy? The children could devise drama scenes showing people’s reactions or create newspaper stories with a bias for or against Darwin and his ideas. (See <em>Junior Ed <span class="caps">PLUS</span></em>, March ’09 for some background information on the basic principles of natural selection.)</p>


	<p>• <strong>Challenging ideas (PSHE):</strong> Ask the children to imagine themselves in Darwin’s shoes. How might he have felt about making public an idea that he knew would outrage society? Can they think of other examples in which someone has risked ridicule to stand up for something they believed in?</p>


	<p><a href="#top">Back to top</a></p>


	<h3 id="fifththing">Friday (cross curricular)</h3>


	<p>• <strong>Celebrating Darwin (cross curricular):</strong> Conclude the theme week with an assembly. ‘Darwin’ could return to answer the children’s questions and award a prize for a child who has answered their <a href="http://magazines.scholastic.co.uk/resources/49575">‘Darwin trivia challenge’</a> correctly. The children could present dances/sketches or show work that they have created throughout the week by creating their own Darwin mini museum (<a href="http://magazines.scholastic.co.uk/resources/48161">see ideas for setting up your own school museum</a>).</p>


